msgid "A serial console bridge (vsock client, debug mode only)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:73
msgid ""
"Communication to the Nitro Enclave is limited to virtio-vsock. The Enclave "
"is allocated a CID at launch at which it is reachable. A specific CID can be "
"requested with ``-accel nitro,enclave-cid=<N>`` (0 lets the hypervisor "
"choose). The assigned CID is readable from the vsock bridge device::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:78
msgid "(qemu) qom-get /machine/peripheral/nitro-vsock enclave-cid"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:81
msgid "EIF Image Format"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:83
msgid ""
"Nitro Enclaves boot from EIF (Enclave Image Format) files. When ``-kernel`` "
"points to an EIF file (detected by the ``.eif`` magic bytes), it is loaded "
"directly into guest memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:87
msgid ""
"When ``-kernel`` points to a regular kernel image (e.g. a bzImage or Image), "
"the machine automatically assembles a minimal EIF on the fly from ``-"
"kernel``, ``-initrd``, and ``-append``. This allows standard direct kernel "
"boot without external EIF tooling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:93
msgid "CPU Requirements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:95
msgid ""
"Nitro Enclaves require full physical CPU cores. On hyperthreaded systems, "
"this means ``-smp`` must be a multiple of the threads per core (typically 2)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:99
msgid ""
"Nitro Enclaves can only consume cores that are donated to the Nitro Enclave "
"CPU pool. You can configure the CPU pool using the ``nitro-enclaves-"
"allocator`` tool or manually by writing to the nitro_enclaves cpu pool "
"parameter. To allocate vCPUs 1, 2 and 3, you can call::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:104
msgid "$ echo 1,2,3 | sudo tee /sys/module/nitro_enclaves/parameters/ne_cpus"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:106
msgid ""
"Beware that on x86-64 systems, hyperthread siblings are not consecutive and "
"must be added in pairs to the pool. Consult tools like ``lstopo`` or "
"``lscpu`` for details about your instance's CPU topology."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:111
msgid "Memory Requirements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:113
msgid ""
"Enclave memory must be huge page backed. The machine automatically creates a "
"memfd memory backend with huge pages enabled. To make the huge page "
"allocation work, ensure that huge pages are reserved in the system. To "
"reserve 1 GiB of memory on a 4 KiB PAGE_SIZE system, you can call::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:119
msgid "$ echo 512 | sudo tee /proc/sys/vm/nr_hugepages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:122
msgid "Emulated Nitro Enclaves"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:124
msgid ""
"In addition to the native Nitro Enclaves invocation, you can also use the "
"emulated nitro-enclave machine target (see :doc:`i386/nitro-enclave`) which "
"implements the x86 Nitro Enclave device model. While -M nitro delegates "
"virtual machine device emulation to the Nitro Hypervisor, -M nitro-enclave "
"implements all devices itself, which means it also works on non-EC2 "
"instances."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../system/nitro.rst:131
msgid ""
"If you require NSM based attestation backed by valid AWS certificates, you "
"must use -M nitro. The -M nitro-enclave model does not provide you with an "
"AWS signed attestation document."
msgstr ""
